  "text": "Many published reports from Western cohorts have analyzed NP data in mixed cohorts of treated and untreated volunteers (e.g., [CITATION_1] . This mixture of potentially disparate groups may have accounted for the weakening of the associations between NP impairment and other biological indicators, such as HIV RNA levels, that have been observed in ''post-HAART'' cohorts. In addition, we found that treated HIV' individuals in comparison to untreated HIV' individuals were more likely to be globally impaired (45% versus 26%, P B.005) and, among those who are impaired, have worse performance (mean GDS 1.1 versus 0.82, P 0.02). The possible explanations for this observation include that treated individuals were also more likely to have AIDS as compared to untreated individuals (75% versus 30%, P B.001) and that those treated with neurotoxic dideoxynucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitors (dNRTIs) tended towards having worse global NP performance when compared to those who did not (mean Global Deficit Score 0.61 versus 0.36, P 0.07).",
